Freons and chlorofluorocarbon find their way to stratosphere through without being destroyed in the troposphere due to their low reactivity. In the stratosphere the $\mathrm{Cl}$ and $\mathrm{Br}$ atoms are liberated from the parent compounds by the action of ultraviolet light e.g.
$$
\begin{aligned}
&\mathrm{CF}_2 \mathrm{Cl}_2+h v \longrightarrow \mathrm{CF}_2 \mathrm{Cl}+\mathrm{Cl} \\
&\mathrm{CFCl}_3+h v \longrightarrow \mathrm{CFCl}_2+\mathrm{Cl}
\end{aligned}
$$
The $\mathrm{Cl}$ atoms can destroy ozone molecules through a variety of catalytic cycles.
